Silly concept all around.<br>
<br>
I travel Norrath to have adventure not to go about willy-nilly &quot;Oh my beloved is here and all is right with the world&quot;.<br>
<br>
And if two more love birds sit there facing each other having &quot;tells&quot; of sweet nothings while the battle is going on and my life bar is traveling right to left rapidly I will do some thing I have never done yet. Which is disband at the first oppertunity. No words, nothing just walk away.<br>
<br>
If EQ romance is for you, Great have fun. But keep it out of the field. focus on your group, they are the first priority. If you want to have romantic time go find a quiet spot with just the two of you (or what ever accumulated number you choose).<br>
<br>
And I add to this those that feel they can carry on several different conversations in tells while thier group is in battle. MAKE UP YOUR MIND. Be with the group you are with or go be with the ones you are in &quot;tells&quot; with.<br>
<br>
Disclaimer: This does not mean you ignore tells, it means you tell them you are busy and will talk later. Later during down time you let the group know you are in tells and will not be battle ready or even disband so you can chatter away.<br>
<br>
/rant off <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/upentapod.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Pentapod</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://members.ozemail.com.au/~pentapod/graphics/a_pod.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>WTB phat newt</span><br>  Posts: 1061<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/30/02 12:53:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2814.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.ozemail.com.au/~pentapod/miscpics/couple.jpg height=200 width=100.gif></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Reply to Siffo</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>   Silly concept all around.<br>
<br>
I travel Norrath to have adventure not to go about willy-nilly &quot;Oh my beloved is here and all is right with the world&quot;.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I too travel Norrath to have adventures.  (Read my diary if you don't believe me.)  And I don't wander around saying anything so silly as the above, although Didi happens to be married.  I fail to see your point.  It's NOT a silly concept.  Marriage is the single most important event in your adult life, at least till you have kids.  It shapes and changes your character.  How you treat your spouse and your relationship defines your character.  As such, I would say that it's extremely important whether you are married or not, and your attitude to marriage.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>   If EQ romance is for you, Great have fun. But keep it out of the field. focus on your group, they are the first priority. If you want to have romantic time go find a quiet spot with just the two of you (or what ever accumulated number you choose).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Again I fail to see your point.  What does EQ romance have to do with roleplaying a marriage?  NOTHING.  Am I , Didi's player, looking for EQ romance from Tallonar's player?  No.  He lives on another continent, for goodness' sake, and is nearly a decade younger than me anyway.  Didi is married, not her player...<br>
<br>
And as for fighting, fighting time is fighting time.  If I happen to be grouped with my husband, you can be damn sure I'll be paying as close attention to the fight as possible, to make sure I don't do anything wrong that would cause him damage.  Anybody who ignores their group to whisper sweet nothings at each other is an IDIOT, end of story.  And that has nothing to do with roleplayed marriage.<br>
<br>
Marrying Tallonar has helped to shape and define Didi's character immeasurably.  They were engaged when she was 16th rank, so reaching 20th rank to marry and take his surname became an important goal (since I was an officer since 18, I had lots of other distractions to take me away from hunting).  Having a husband working towards grandmaster smithing status also shapes Didi's goals and hunting patterns - animal pelts, spiderling silks, shadowed men, looks like windstones are in my future now I'm 41.  (He tends to show up and say &quot;Hi hun ... happen to have any leather paddings I could have?&quot; - now there's romance! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )  Why do you think I'm so proud of my faction standing with shadowed men (see my sig...)?  Because it was for Tallonar's smithing.  By the time I could solo shadowed men they were light blue to me - think I was getting experience fighting them for 2 months or however long it was?  Not hardly.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
In actual RL fact, I haven't seen Tallonar in-game for about 2 months, between our different time zones and his ISP problems.  (And no, unlike Ulec, his player doesn't have my phone number, in fact I don't think he even knows my real name.)  That doesn't change anything about the fact that Didi is in a roleplayed marriage.  If Tallonar never appeared in Norrath again, it wouldn't actually make a difference to Didi's roleplay.  She's still married to Tallonar, she's still faithful and loyal and devoted to him, he still means all the world to her, and her character and actions are shaped accordingly.  <br>
<br>
While I can understand you'd rightly be annoyed at people who prefer to cyber rather than fight, you haven't actually said anything whatsoever pertinent to the topic, which is roleplayed marriages.<br>
<br>
